  "prompt": "How does one juggle?",
  "response": "Juggling is a skill that involves keeping multiple objects, usually balls, clubs, or rings, in motion in the air by catching and throwing them in a rhythmical pattern. Here\u2019s a basic guide on how to start juggling with three balls, which is the most common beginner technique:\n\n1. **Choose the Right Balls:**\n   - Use juggling balls that are soft and not too big. Beanbag-style balls are ideal because they are easy to catch and don't roll away when dropped.\n\n2. **Start with One Ball:**\n   - Practice tossing a single ball from one hand to the other. Aim for a consistent arc that reaches about eye level.\n\n3. **Progress to Two Balls:**\n   - Hold one ball in each hand.\n   - Toss the ball in your dominant hand in an arc to the other hand. As it peaks, toss the second ball in an arc from the other hand back to the first hand.\n   - Practice the exchange. Both balls should describe similar arcs and heights.\n\n4. **Introduce the Third Ball:**\n   - Start with two balls in your dominant hand and one in the other.\n   - Throw the first ball from your dominant hand. When it peaks, throw the ball from your other hand.\n   - As the second ball peaks, throw the third ball.\n   - The pattern you'll aim to achieve is called a \"cascade,\" where each hand throws one ball at a consistent rhythm.\n\n5. **Practice the Cascade Pattern:**\n   - The cascade pattern involves continuously catching and throwing the balls so that they move in a smooth, circular motion.\n   - Focus on keeping your throws consistent and at a manageable height.\n\n6. **Keep Hands Relaxed:**\n   - Avoid tensing your shoulders and arms. Keep them relaxed to make smoother and more controlled throws.\n\n7. **Practice Regularly:**\n   - Like any skill, juggling requires regular practice. Even a few minutes a day can lead to improvement.\n\n8. **Stay Patient:**\n   - Expect to drop the balls often at first. Learning to juggle takes time and patience, and dropping is part of the learning process.\n\nBy following these steps, beginners can gradually learn the fundamental skills needed to juggle three balls and progress to more advanced techniques and tricks over time.",
